The drain event fires from inside a write callback when `_inFlightWrites <= 0 && !_waitForDrain`. With 3 keys written in one batch (original), all 3 writes are in-flight. The drain fires when the last write completes. But the callbacks fire in order - so when the 3rd write callback fires (triggering drain), callbacks 1 and 2 have already fired, but callback 3 fires in the same tick as drain.

So at drain time: callbacks 1 and 2 fired = count is 2, then callback 3 fires = count becomes 3, then drain fires. That's why we see 2 at drain time.

